\begin_layout Section
Tax salience and welfare
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a set-up similar to problem 1, where consumers have 
\emph on
true
\emph default
 utility given by 
\begin_inset Formula $U(x)=u(x)+(y-(p+t)x)$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that instead of maximizing 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, consumers choose 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to maximize 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)+(y-(p+\theta t)x)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the tax salience parameter.
 Suppose that the government wants to maximize social welfare, given by
 
\begin_inset Formula $W(t)=U(x^{*})+\lambda tx^{*}(t)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $tx^{*}(t)$
\end_inset

 is the tax revenue and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\geq1$
\end_inset

 is the value of public funds.
 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=ax-\frac{1}{2}x^{2}$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $a>p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
2.1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a consumer with salience parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, show that the demand is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}(t)=\max(a-p-\theta t,0)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
2.2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prove that for 
\begin_inset Formula $p+\theta t<a$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d}{dt}U(x^{*}(t))=-x^{*}+(1-\theta)\theta t=p+\theta t-a+(1-\theta)\theta t$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
2.3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prove that the tax 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 that maximizes 
\begin_inset Formula $W(t)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\frac{(\lambda-1)(a-p)}{2\theta(\lambda-1)+\theta^{2}}$
\end_inset

 (assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $a>p+\theta t$
\end_inset

 at that value), and thus that the optimal tax is decreasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Prove also that 
\begin_inset Formula $\max_{t}W(t)$
\end_inset

, the maximum obtainable welfare, is decreasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 What is the intuition?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
2.4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose now that a fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 of consumers have 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\theta_{l}$
\end_inset

 and a fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\alpha$
\end_inset

 of consumers have 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\theta_{h}$
\end_inset

.
 Let social welfare be 
\begin_inset Formula $W=\alpha U(x_{l}^{*})+(1-\alpha)U(x_{h}^{*})+\lambda[\alpha tx_{l}^{*}(t)+(1-\alpha)tx_{h}^{*}(t)]$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{l}^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{h}^{*}$
\end_inset

 are the demands of type 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{l}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{h}$
\end_inset

 consumers, respectively.
 Prove that the tax 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 that maximizes 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\frac{(\lambda-1)(a-p)}{2E[\theta](\lambda-1)+E[\theta]^{2}+Var[\theta]}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $E[\theta]$
\end_inset

 is the average 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 in the population and 
\begin_inset Formula $Var[\theta]$
\end_inset

 is its variance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
2.5 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Together, parts c and d show that holding constant the average value of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 in the population, the optimal tax is decreasing in the variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 What is the intuition?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
2.6
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prove that even when 
\begin_inset Formula $E[\theta]<1$
\end_inset

, welfare would be higher if both types of consumers perceived the tax correctly
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{h}$
\end_inset

 is sufficiently high to make 
\begin_inset Formula $Var[\theta]>1$
\end_inset

.
 Draw a contrast to your answer in 2.3, and discuss the intuition.
\end_layout

